      "description": "\u201cTrapped in their cozy catacombs, the couples have made sex by turns their toy, their glue, their trauma, their therapy, their hope, their frustration, their revenge, their narcotic, their main line of communication and their sole and pitiable shield against the awareness of death.\u201d\u2014Time One of the signature novels of the American 1960s, Couples is a book that, when it debuted, scandalized the public with prose pictures of the way people live, and that today provides an engrossing epitaph to the short, happy life of the \u201cpost-Pill paradise.\u201d It chronicles the interactions of ten young married couples in a seaside New England community who make a cult of sex and of themselves. The group of acquaintances form a magical circle, complete with ritualistic games, religious substitutions, a priest (Freddy Thorne), and a scapegoat (Piet Hanema). As with most American utopias, this one\u2019s existence is brief and unsustainable, but the \u201cimaginative quest\u201d that inspires its creation is eternal. Praise for Couples \u201cCouples [is] John Updike\u2019s tour de force of extramarital wanderlust.\u201d\u2014The New York Times Book Review \u201cIngenious . . . If this is a dirty book, I don\u2019t see how sex can be written about at all.\u201d\u2014Wilfrid Sheed, The New York Times Book Review",
